In United States federal legislation, the '''Indian Education and Self-Assistance Act (Snyder Act)''' was passed in 1917 and sponsored by Rep. [[Homer P. Snyder]] (R) of New York.
It empowered the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]], under the Secretary of the Interior, to appropriate money for the general improvement of the quality of life among [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] on reservations including adult [[literacy]] programs and health care facilities. Although a step in the right direction, the appropriations provided for the next several decades still proved inadequate to what was needed.
