{{Politics of Niue}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Niue]] on 13 June 1992.<ref name=SPC>[http://www.spc.int/prism/Country/NU/stats/Reports/Abstracts/Niue%20Abstracts_Part1_A.pdf Niue: General Information] Secretariat of the Pacific Community</ref> The proposed amendments to the [[Niue Constitution Act|constitution]] were the first since the country's original constitution was approved in a [[Niuean constitutional referendum, 1974|1974 referendum]].<ref name=SPC/> The changes were approved by a large majority of voters.<ref>[http://www.bayefsky.com/reports/newzealand_e_1990_5_add_12_1992.pdf Initial reports submitted by State parties under articles 16 and 17 of the covenant] United Nations</ref>
==Proposed changes== The changes to the constitution included the introduction of the Niuean High Court and Court of Appeal, replacing the use of the equivalent courts in [[New Zealand]].<ref name=UPF>[http://www.upf.pf/IMG/pdf/12-RJP15-Pacific-Constitutions.pdf Pacific Constitutions - Overview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305064608/http://www.upf.pf/IMG/pdf/12-RJP15-Pacific-Constitutions.pdf |date=2012-03-05 }} University of French Polynesia</ref> The reforms also abolished the Niue Land Court and the Niue Land Appeal Court, instead creating a Land Division in the new High Court.<ref name=UPF/>
Qualifications for political candidates were amended to require New Zealand citizenship.<ref name=UPF/> It also removed article 31, a requirement for the Chief Justice to approve any legislative proposal that would affect criminal law or personal status.<ref name=UPF/> This effectively removed the human rights element of the constitution.<ref name=UPF/>
==Aftermath== Following the approval of the changes, there was subsequent criticism that the individual changes should have been voted on separately, as well as of the removal of article 31.<ref name=UPF/>
